# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agent-based-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] An **agent-based model** (**ABM**) is a computational model for simulating the actions and interactions of an autonomous agent (both individual or collective entities such as organizations or groups) to understand the behavior of a system and what governs its outcomes.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] It combines elements of game theory, complex systems, emergence, computational sociology, multi-agent systems, and evolutionary programming.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Monte Carlo methods are used to understand the stochasticity of these models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Particularly within ecology, an ABM is also called an **individual-based model** (**IBM**).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] A review of literature on individual-based models, agent-based models, and multiagent systems shows that ABMs are used in many scientific domains including biology, ecology, and social science.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling is related to, but distinct from, the concept of a **multi-agent system** .
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is a type of microscale model that simulates the simultaneous operations and interactions of multiple agents in an attempt to re-create and predict the appearance of complex phenomena.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The process is one of emergence, which some express as "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In other words, higher-level system properties emerge from the interactions of lower-level subsystems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Or, macro-scale state changes emerge from micro-scale agent behaviors.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Or, simple behaviors (meaning rules followed by agents) generate complex behaviors (meaning state changes at the whole system level).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] An individual agent is typically characterized as boundedly rational, presumed to be acting in what it perceives as its their own interests, such as reproduction, economic benefit, or social status, using heuristics or simple decision-making rules.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] An ABM agent may experience "learning", adaptation, and reproduction.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is usually composed of (1) numerous agents specified at various scales (typically referred to as agent-granularity), (2) decision-making heuristics, (3) learning rules or adaptive processes,(4) an interaction topology, and (5) an environment.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] An ABM is typically implemented as a computer simulation, either as custom software or using an ABM toolkit.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] This software can be then used to test how changes in individual behavior will affect the system's overall behavior.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The idea of agent-based modeling was developed as a relatively simple concept in the late 1940s.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Since it requires computation-intensive procedures, it did not become widespread until the 1990s.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The history of the agent-based model can be traced back to the Von Neumann machine, a theoretical machine capable of reproduction.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The device von Neumann proposed would follow precisely detailed instructions to fashion a copy of itself.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The concept was then built upon by von Neumann's friend Stanislaw Ulam, also a mathematician; Ulam suggested that the machine be built on paper, as a collection of cells on a grid.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The idea intrigued von Neumann, who drew it up — creating the first of the devices later termed cellular automata.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Oliver Selfridge's 1958 Pandemonium - A Paradigm for Learning paper was an important early theorectical contribution in establishing agent orientated architecture, though it used the term metaphorical 'demon' instead of agent.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Carl Hewitt 1973 Actor model contained one of the earliest uses of agents as active entities rather than passive structures.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Another advance was introduced by the mathematician John Conway.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] He constructed the well-known Game of Life.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Unlike von Neumann's machine, the Game of Life operated by simple rules in a virtual world in the form of a 2-dimensional checkerboard.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The Simula programming language, developed in the mid-1960s and widely implemented by the early 1970s, was the first framework for automating step-by-step agent simulations.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] One of the earliest agent-based models in concept was Thomas Schelling's segregation model, which was discussed in his paper "Dynamic Models of Segregation" in 1971.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Though Schelling originally used coins and graph paper rather than computers, his models embodied the basic concept of agent-based models as autonomous agents interacting in a shared environment with an observed aggregate, emergent outcome.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In the late 1970s, Paulien Hogeweg and Bruce Hesper began experimenting with individual models of ecology.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] One of their first results was to show that the social structure of bumble-bee colonies emerged as a result of simple rules that govern the behaviour of individual bees.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] They introduced the ToDo principle, referring to the way agents "do what there is to do" at any given time.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In the early 1980s, Robert Axelrod hosted a tournament of Prisoner's Dilemma strategies and had them interact in an agent-based manner to determine a winner.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Axelrod would go on to develop many other agent-based models in the field of political science that examine phenomena from ethnocentrism to the dissemination of culture.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] By the late 1980s, Craig Reynolds' work on flocking models contributed to the development of some of the first biological agent-based models that contained social characteristics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] He tried to model the reality of lively biological agents, known as artificial life, a term coined by Christopher Langton.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] At the same time, during the 1980s, social scientists, mathematicians, operations researchers, and a scattering of people from other disciplines developed Computational and Mathematical Organization Theory (CMOT).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] This field grew as a special interest group of The Institute of Management Sciences (TIMS) and its sister society, the Operations Research Society of America (ORSA).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The 1990s were especially notable for the expansion of ABM within the social sciences, one notable effort was the large-scale ABM, Sugarscape, developed by Joshua M.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Epstein and Robert Axtell to simulate and explore the role of social phenomena such as seasonal migrations, pollution, sexual reproduction, combat, and transmission of disease and even culture.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Other notable 1990s developments included Carnegie Mellon University's Kathleen Carley ABM, to explore the co-evolution of social networks and culture.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The Santa Fe Institute (SFI) was important in encouraging the development of the ABM modeling platform Swarm under the leadership of Christopher Langton.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Research conducted through SFI allowed the expansion of ABM techniques to a number of fields including study of the social and spatial dynamics of small-scale human societies and primates.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] During this 1990s timeframe Nigel Gilbert published the first textbook on Social Simulation: Simulation for the social scientist (1999) and established a journal from the perspective of social sciences: the *Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation* (JASSS).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Other than JASSS, agent-based models of any discipline are within scope of SpringerOpen journal *Complex Adaptive Systems Modeling* (CASM).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Through the mid-1990s, the social sciences thread of ABM began to focus on such issues as designing effective teams, understanding the communication required for organizational effectiveness, and the behavior of social networks.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] CMOT—later renamed Computational Analysis of Social and Organizational Systems (CASOS)—incorporated more and more agent-based modeling.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Samuelson (2000) is a good brief overview of the early history, and Samuelson (2005) and Samuelson and Macal (2006) trace the more recent developments.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In the late 1990s, the merger of TIMS and ORSA to form INFORMS, and the move by INFORMS from two meetings each year to one, helped to spur the CMOT group to form a separate society, the North American Association for Computational Social and Organizational Sciences (NAACSOS).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Kathleen Carley was a major contributor, especially to models of social networks, obtaining National Science Foundation funding for the annual conference and serving as the first president of NAACSOS.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] She was succeeded by David Sallach of the University of Chicago and Argonne National Laboratory, and then by Michael Prietula of Emory University.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] At about the same time NAACSOS began, the European Social Simulation Association (ESSA) and the Pacific Asian Association for Agent-Based Approach in Social Systems Science (PAAA), counterparts of NAACSOS, were organized.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] As of 2013, these three organizations collaborate internationally.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The First World Congress on Social Simulation was held under their joint sponsorship in Kyoto, Japan, in August 2006.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The Second World Congress was held in the northern Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., in July 2008, with George Mason University taking the lead role in local arrangements.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] More recently, Ron Sun developed methods for basing agent-based simulation on models of human cognition, known as cognitive social simulation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Bill McKelvey, Suzanne Lohmann, Dario Nardi, Dwight Read and others at UCLA have also made significant contributions in organizational behavior and decision-making.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Since 1991, UCLA has arranged a conference at Lake Arrowhead, California, that has become another major gathering point for practitioners in this field.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] After the advent of large language models, researchers began applying interacting language models to agent based modeling.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In one widely cited paper, agentic language models interacted in a sandbox environment to perform activities like planning birthday parties and holding elections.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Most computational modeling research describes systems in equilibrium or as moving between equilibria.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling, however, using simple rules, can result in different sorts of complex and interesting behavior.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The three ideas central to agent-based models are agents as objects, emergence, and complexity.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models consist of dynamically interacting rule-based agents.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The systems within which they interact can create real-world-like complexity.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Typically agents are situated in space and time and reside in networks or in lattice-like neighborhoods.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The location of the agents and their responsive behavior are encoded in algorithmic form in computer programs.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In some cases, though not always, the agents may be considered as intelligent and purposeful.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In ecological ABM (often referred to as "individual-based models" in ecology), agents may, for example, be trees in a forest, and would not be considered intelligent, although they may be "purposeful" in the sense of optimizing access to a resource (such as water).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The modeling process is best described as inductive.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The modeler makes those assumptions thought most relevant to the situation at hand and then watches phenomena emerge from the agents' interactions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Sometimes that result is an equilibrium.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Sometimes, however, it is an unintelligible mangle.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In some ways, agent-based models complement traditional analytic methods.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Where analytic methods enable humans to characterize the equilibria of a system, agent-based models allow the possibility of generating those equilibria.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] This generative contribution may be the most mainstream of the potential benefits of agent-based modeling.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models can explain the emergence of higher-order patterns—network structures of terrorist organizations and the Internet, power-law distributions in the sizes of traffic jams, wars, and stock-market crashes, and social segregation that persists despite populations of tolerant people.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models also can be used to identify lever points, defined as moments in time in which interventions have extreme consequences, and to distinguish among types of path dependency.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Rather than focusing on stable states, many models consider a system's robustness—the ways that complex systems adapt to internal and external pressures so as to maintain their functionalities.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The task of harnessing that complexity requires consideration of the agents themselves—their diversity, connectedness, and level of interactions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Exploratory Agent-based Modeling Level for developing agent-based models for assessing the feasibility of further research.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] This can e.g. be useful for developing proof-of-concept models such as for funding applications without requiring an extensive learning curve for the researchers.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Descriptive Agent-based Modeling (DREAM) for developing descriptions of agent-based models by means of using templates and complex network-based models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Building DREAM models allows model comparison across scientific disciplines.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Validated agent-based modeling using Virtual Overlay Multiagent system (VOMAS) for the development of verified and validated models in a formal manner.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Other methods of describing agent-based models include code templates and text-based methods such as the ODD (Overview, Design concepts, and Design Details) protocol.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The role of the environment where agents live, both macro and micro, is also becoming an important factor in agent-based modelling and simulation work.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Simple environment affords simple agents, but complex environments generate diversity of behavior.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] One strength of agent-based modelling is its ability to mediate information flow between scales.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] When additional details about an agent are needed, a researcher can integrate it with models describing the extra details.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] When one is interested in the emergent behaviours demonstrated by the agent population, they can combine the agent-based model with a continuum model describing population dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In the resulting modular model, signal transduction and gene regulation are described by a logical model, metabolism by constraint-based models, cell population dynamics are described by an agent-based model, and systemic cytokine concentrations by ordinary differential equations.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In this multi-scale model, the agent-based model occupies the central place and orchestrates every stream of information flow between scales.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been used for developing decision support systems such as for breast cancer.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models are increasingly being used to model pharmacological systems in early stage and pre-clinical research to aid in drug development and gain insights into biological systems that would not be possible *a priori*.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Military applications have also been evaluated.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Moreover, agent-based models have been recently employed to study molecular-level biological systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been written to describe ecological processes at work in ancient systems, such as those in dinosaur environments and more recent ancient systems as well.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models now complement traditional compartmental models, the usual type of epidemiological models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs have been shown to be superior to compartmental models in regard to the accuracy of predictions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Recently, ABMs such as CovidSim by epidemiologist Neil Ferguson, have been used to inform public health (nonpharmaceutical) interventions against the spread of SARS-CoV-2.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Epidemiological ABMs have been criticized for simplifying and unrealistic assumptions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Still, they can be useful in informing decisions regarding mitigation and suppression measures in cases when ABMs are accurately calibrated.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The ABMs for such simulations are mostly based on synthetic populations, since the data of the actual population is not always available.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have been used since the mid-1990s to solve a variety of business and technology problems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Examples of applications include marketing, organizational behaviour and cognition, team working, supply chain optimization and logistics, modeling of consumer behavior, including word of mouth, social network effects, distributed computing, workforce management, and portfolio management.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] They have also been used to analyze traffic congestion.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Recently, agent based modelling and simulation has been applied to various domains such as studying the impact of publication venues by researchers in the computer science domain (journals versus conferences).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In addition, ABMs have been used to simulate information delivery in ambient assisted environments.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] A November 2016 article in arXiv analyzed an agent based simulation of posts spread in Facebook.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In the domain of peer-to-peer, ad hoc and other self-organizing and complex networks, the usefulness of agent based modeling and simulation has been shown.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The use of a computer science-based formal specification framework coupled with wireless sensor networks and an agent-based simulation has recently been demonstrated.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent based evolutionary search or algorithm is a new research topic for solving complex optimization problems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] In the realm of team science, agent-based modeling has been utilized to assess the effects of team members' characteristics and biases on team performance across various settings.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] By simulating interactions between agents—each representing individual team members with distinct traits and biases—this modeling approach enables researchers to explore how these factors collectively influence the dynamics and outcomes of team performance.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Consequently, agent-based modeling provides a nuanced understanding of team science, facilitating a deeper exploration of the subtleties and variabilities inherent in team-based collaborations.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Prior to, and during the 2008 financial crisis, interest has grown in ABMs as possible tools for economic analysis.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs do not assume the economy can achieve equilibrium and "representative agents" are replaced by agents with diverse, dynamic, and interdependent behavior including herding.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs take a "bottom-up" approach and can generate extremely complex and volatile simulated economies.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs can represent unstable systems with crashes and booms that develop out of non-linear (disproportionate) responses to proportionally small changes.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] A July 2010 article in *The Economist* looked at ABMs as alternatives to DSGE models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The journal *Nature* also encouraged agent-based modeling with an editorial that suggested ABMs can do a better job of representing financial markets and other economic complexities than standard models along with an essay by J.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Doyne Farmer and Duncan Foley that argued ABMs could fulfill both the desires of Keynes to represent a complex economy and of Robert Lucas to construct models based on microfoundations.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Farmer and Foley pointed to progress that has been made using ABMs to model parts of an economy, but argued for the creation of a very large model that incorporates low level models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] By modeling a complex system of analysts based on three distinct behavioral profiles – imitating, anti-imitating, and indifferent – financial markets were simulated to high accuracy.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Results showed a correlation between network morphology and the stock market index.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] However, the ABM approach has been criticized for its lack of robustness between models, where similar models can yield very different results.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs have been deployed in architecture and urban planning to evaluate design and to simulate pedestrian flow in the urban environment and the examination of public policy applications to land-use.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] There is also a growing field of socio-economic analysis of infrastructure investment impact using ABM's ability to discern systemic impacts upon a socio-economic network.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Heterogeneity and dynamics can be easily built in ABM models to address wealth inequality and social mobility.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been proposed as applied educational tools for diplomats in the field of international relations and for domestic and international policymakers to enhance their evaluation of public policy.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been applied in water resources planning and management, particularly for exploring, simulating, and predicting the performance of infrastructure design and policy decisions, and in assessing the value of cooperation and information exchange in large water resources systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agents for Systems are divided in two subcategories.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-supported systems deal with the use of agents as a support facility to enable computer assistance in problem solving or enhancing cognitive capabilities.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Agent-based systems focus on the use of agents for the generation of model behavior in a system evaluation (system studies and analyses).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Hallerbach et al. discussed the application of agent-based approaches for the development and validation of automated driving systems via a digital twin of the vehicle-under-test and microscopic traffic simulation based on independent agents.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Waymo has created a multi-agent simulation environment Carcraft to test algorithms for self-driving cars.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] It simulates traffic interactions between human drivers, pedestrians and automated vehicles.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] People's behavior is imitated by artificial agents based on data of real human behavior.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The basic idea of using agent-based modeling to understand self-driving cars was discussed as early as 2003.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Many ABM frameworks are designed for serial von-Neumann computer architectures, limiting the speed and scalability of implemented models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Since emergent behavior in large-scale ABMs is dependent of population size, scalability restrictions may hinder model validation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Such limitations have mainly been addressed using distributed computing, with frameworks such as Repast HPC specifically dedicated to these types of implementations.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] While such approaches map well to cluster and supercomputer architectures, issues related to communication and synchronization, as well as deployment complexity, remain potential obstacles for their widespread adoption.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] A recent development is the use of data-parallel algorithms on Graphics Processing Units GPUs for ABM simulation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] The extreme memory bandwidth combined with the sheer number crunching power of multi-processor GPUs has enabled simulation of millions of agents at tens of frames per second.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Since Agent-Based Modeling is more of a modeling framework than a particular piece of software or platform, it has often been used in conjunction with other modeling forms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] For instance, agent-based models have also been combined with Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] This provides a useful combination where the ABM serves as a process model and the GIS system can provide a model of pattern.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Similarly, Social Network Analysis (SNA) tools and agent-based models are sometimes integrated, where the ABM is used to simulate the dynamics on the network while the SNA tool models and analyzes the network of interactions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Tools like GAMA provide a natural way to integrate system dynamics and GIS with ABM.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Verification and validation (V&V) of simulation models is extremely important.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Verification involves making sure the implemented model matches the conceptual model, whereas validation ensures that the implemented model has some relationship to the real-world.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Face validation, sensitivity analysis, calibration, and statistical validation are different aspects of validation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] A discrete-event simulation framework approach for the validation of agent-based systems has been proposed.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] A comprehensive resource on empirical validation of agent-based models can be found here.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] As an example of V&V technique, consider VOMAS (virtual overlay multi-agent system), a software engineering based approach, where a virtual overlay multi-agent system is developed alongside the agent-based model.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Muazi et al. also provide an example of using VOMAS for verification and validation of a forest fire simulation model.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Another software engineering method, i.e.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] Test-Driven Development has been adapted to for agent-based model validation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/agent-based-model] This approach has another advantage that allows an automatic validation using unit test tools.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] A **complex adaptive system** (**CAS**) is a system that is *complex* in that it is a dynamic network of interactions, but the behavior of the ensemble may not be predictable according to the behavior of the components.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] It is *adaptive* in that the individual and collective behavior mutate and self-organize corresponding to the change-initiating micro-event or collection of events.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] It is a "complex macroscopic collection" of relatively "similar and partially connected micro-structures" formed in order to adapt to the changing environment and increase their survivability as a macro-structure.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] The Complex Adaptive Systems approach builds on replicator dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] CAS is increasingly applied to analyze political-economic development and institutional change, where outcomes emerge from interactions among adaptive agents, and may be influenced but not precisely controlled.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] The term *complex adaptive systems*, or *complexity science*, is often used to describe the loosely organized academic field that has grown up around the study of such systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Complexity science is not a single theory—it encompasses more than one theoretical framework and is interdisciplinary, seeking the answers to some fundamental questions about living, adaptable, changeable systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Complex adaptive systems may adopt hard or softer approaches.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Hard theories use formal language that is precise, tend to see agents as having tangible properties, and usually see objects in a behavioral system that can be manipulated in some way.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Softer theories use natural language and narratives that may be imprecise, and agents are subjects having both tangible and intangible properties.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Examples of hard complexity theories include complex adaptive systems (CAS) and viability theory, and a class of softer theory is Viable System Theory.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Many of the propositional consideration made in hard theory are also of relevance to softer theory.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] From here on, interest will now center on CAS.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] The study of CAS focuses on complex, emergent and macroscopic properties of the system.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Typical examples of complex adaptive systems include: climate; cities; firms; markets; governments; industries; ecosystems; social networks; power grids; animal swarms; traffic flows; social insect (e.g. ant) colonies; the brain and the immune system; and the cell and the developing embryo.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Human social group-based endeavors, such as political parties, communities, geopolitical organizations, war, supply chains and terrorist networks are also considered CAS.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] The internet and cyberspace—composed, collaborated, and managed by a complex mix of human–computer interactions, is also regarded as a complex adaptive system.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] CAS can be hierarchical, but more often exhibit aspects of "self-organization".
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] The term complex adaptive system was coined in 1968 by sociologist Walter F.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Buckley who proposed a model of cultural evolution which regards psychological and socio-cultural systems as analogous with biological species.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] In the modern context, complex adaptive system is sometimes linked to memetics, or proposed as a reformulation of memetics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] As such, complex adaptive system is more similar to Richard Dawkins's idea of replicators.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] What distinguishes a complex adaptive system (CAS) from a pure multi-agent system (MAS) is the focus on top-level properties and features like self-similarity, complexity, emergence and self-organization.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Theorists define an MAS as a system composed of multiple interacting agents; whereas in CAS, the agents as well as the system are adaptive and the system is self-similar.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] A CAS is a complex, self-similar collectivity of interacting, adaptive agents.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Complex adaptive systems feature a high degree of adaptive capacity, giving them resilience in the face of perturbation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Other important properties include adaptation (or homeostasis), communication, cooperation, specialization, spatial and temporal organization, and reproduction.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Such properties can manifest themselves on all levels: cells specialize, adapt and reproduce themselves just like larger organisms do.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Communication and cooperation take place on all levels, from the agent- to the system-level.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] In some cases the forces driving co-operation between agents in such a system can be analyzed using game theory.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Turner and Baker synthesized the characteristics of complex adaptive systems from the literature and tested these characteristics in the context of creativity and innovation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] The organisation of a complex adaptive system rely on the use of internal models, mental models or schemas guiding the behaviors of the system.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] CAS are occasionally modelled by means of agent-based models and complex network-based models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Agent-based models are developed by means of various methods and tools primarily by means of first identifying the different agents inside the model.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Another method of developing models for CAS involves developing complex network models by means of using interaction data of various CAS components.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Models and simulations are often used to study proposed systems phenomena in large infrastructural systems, where empirical testing would be prohibitively expensive and risky.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Examples include those use of applied agent-based and graph-theoretic approaches to digital supply-chain twins and anomaly detection in high-speed networks.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] In 2013 SpringerOpen/BioMed Central launched an online open-access journal on the topic of *complex adaptive systems modelling* (CASM).
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Publication of the journal ceased in 2020.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Living organisms are complex adaptive systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Although complexity is hard to quantify in biology, evolution has produced some remarkably complex organisms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] This observation has led to the common misconception of evolution being progressive and leading towards what are viewed as "higher organisms".
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] If this were generally true, evolution would possess an active trend towards complexity.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] As shown below, in this type of process the value of the most common amount of complexity would increase over time.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Indeed, some artificial life simulations have suggested that the generation of CAS is an inescapable feature of evolution.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] However, the idea of a general trend towards complexity in evolution can also be explained through a passive process.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] This involves an increase in variance but the most common value, the mode, does not change.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Thus, the maximum level of complexity increases over time, but only as an indirect product of there being more organisms in total.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] This type of random process is also called a bounded random walk.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] In this hypothesis, the apparent trend towards more complex organisms is an illusion resulting from concentrating on the small number of large, very complex organisms that inhabit the right-hand tail of the complexity distribution and ignoring simpler and much more common organisms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] This passive model emphasizes that the overwhelming majority of species are microscopic prokaryotes, which comprise about half the world's biomass and constitute the vast majority of Earth's biodiversity.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] Therefore, simple life remains dominant on Earth, and complex life appears more diverse only because of sampling bias.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] If there is a lack of an overall trend towards complexity in biology, this would not preclude the existence of forces driving systems towards complexity in a subset of cases.
[src:agent-based-modeling/complex-adaptive-system] These minor trends would be balanced by other evolutionary pressures that drive systems towards less complex states.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In philosophy, systems theory, science, and art, **emergence** occurs when a complex entity has properties or behaviors that its parts do not have on their own, and emerge only when they interact in a wider whole.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Emergence plays a central role in theories of integrative levels and of complex systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] For instance, the phenomenon of life as studied in biology is an emergent property of chemistry and physics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Philosophers often understand emergence as a claim about the etiology of a system's properties.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] An emergent property of a system, in this context, is one that is not a property of any component of that system, but is still a feature of the system as a whole.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Nicolai Hartmann (1882–1950), one of the first modern philosophers to write on emergence, termed this a *categorial novum* (new category).
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] This concept of emergence dates from at least the time of Aristotle.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In Heideggerian thought, the notion of emergence is derived from the Greek word *poiein*, meaning "to make", and refers to a bringing-forth that encompasses not just a process of crafting (*techne*) but also the broader sense of something coming into being or revealing itself.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Heidegger used emerging blossoms and butterflies as examples to illustrate *poiêsis* as a threshold event where something moves from one state to another.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Many scientists and philosophers have written on the concept, including John Stuart Mill (*Composition of Causes*, 1843) and Julian Huxley (1887–1975).
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Usage of the notion "emergence" may generally be subdivided into two perspectives, that of "weak emergence" and "strong emergence".
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] One paper discussing this division is *Weak Emergence*, by philosopher Mark Bedau.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Crucial in these simulations is that the interacting members retain their independence.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] If not, a new entity is formed with new, emergent properties: this is called strong emergence, which it is argued cannot be simulated, analysed or reduced.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] David Chalmers writes that emergence often causes confusion in philosophy and science due to a failure to demarcate strong and weak emergence, which are "quite different concepts".
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Some common points between the two notions are that emergence concerns new properties produced as the system grows, which is to say ones which are not shared with its components or prior states.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Also, it is assumed that the properties are supervenient rather than metaphysically primitive.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Weak emergence describes new properties arising in systems as a result of the interactions at a fundamental level.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] However, Bedau stipulates that the properties can be determined only by observing or simulating the system, and not by any process of a reductionist analysis.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] As a consequence the emerging properties are **scale dependent**: they are only observable if the system is large enough to exhibit the phenomenon.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Chaotic, unpredictable behaviour can be seen as an emergent phenomenon, while at a microscopic scale the behaviour of the constituent parts can be fully deterministic.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Bedau notes that weak emergence is not a universal metaphysical solvent, as the hypothesis that consciousness is weakly emergent would not resolve the traditional philosophical questions about the physicality of consciousness.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] However, Bedau concludes that adopting this view would provide a precise notion that emergence is involved in consciousness, and second, the notion of weak emergence is metaphysically benign.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Strong emergence describes the direct causal action of a high-level system on its components; qualities produced this way are irreducible to the system's constituent parts.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The whole is other than the sum of its parts.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] It is argued then that no simulation of the system can exist, for such a simulation would itself constitute a reduction of the system to its constituent parts.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Physics lacks well-established examples of strong emergence, unless it is interpreted as the impossibility *in practice* to explain the whole in terms of the parts.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Practical impossibility may be a more useful distinction than one in principle, since it is easier to determine and quantify, and does not imply the use of mysterious forces, but simply reflects the limits of our capability.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] One of the reasons for the importance of distinguishing these two concepts with respect to their difference concerns the relationship of purported emergent properties to science.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Some thinkers question the plausibility of strong emergence as contravening our usual understanding of physics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The concern that strong emergence does so entail is that such a consequence must be incompatible with metaphysical principles such as the principle of sufficient reason or the Latin dictum *ex nihilo nihil fit*, often translated as "nothing comes from nothing".
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Strong emergence can be criticized for leading to causal overdetermination.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The canonical example concerns emergent mental states (M and M∗) that supervene on physical states (P and P∗) respectively.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] If M is the cause of M∗, then M∗ is overdetermined because M∗ can also be thought of as being determined by P.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] One escape-route that a strong emergentist could take would be to deny downward causation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] However, this would remove the proposed reason that emergent mental states must supervene on physical states, which in turn would call physicalism into question, and thus be unpalatable for some philosophers and physicists.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Carroll and Parola propose a taxonomy that classifies emergent phenomena by how the macro-description relates to the underlying micro-dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] that commutes with time evolution, without requiring any further decomposition into subsystems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Emergence where the macro theory is defined in terms of localized collections of micro-subsystems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Type‑1a (Direct) Emergence: When the emergence map Φ is algorithmically simple (i.e. compressible), so that the macro behavior is easily deduced from the micro-states.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Type‑1b (Incompressible) Emergence: When Φ is algorithmically complex (i.e. incompressible), making the macro behavior appear more novel despite being determined by the micro-dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Cases in which both the micro and macro theories admit subsystem decompositions, yet the macro entities are defined nonlocally with respect to the micro-structure, meaning that macro behavior depends on widely distributed micro information.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] A form of strong emergence in which the macro theory introduces additional ontological variables that do not supervene on the micro-states, thereby positing genuinely novel macro-level entities.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Crutchfield regards the properties of complexity and organization of any system as subjective qualities determined by the observer.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The low entropy of an ordered system can be viewed as an example of subjective emergence: the observer sees an ordered system by ignoring the underlying microstructure (i.e. movement of molecules or elementary particles) and concludes that the system has a low entropy.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] On the other hand, chaotic, unpredictable behaviour can also be seen as subjective emergent, while at a microscopic scale the movement of the constituent parts can be fully deterministic.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In physics, *weak* emergence is used to describe a property, law, or phenomenon which occurs at macroscopic scales (in space or time) but not at microscopic scales, despite the fact that a macroscopic system can be viewed as a very large ensemble of microscopic systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] As a result, these macroscopic systems are described in their own terminology, and have properties that do not depend on many microscopic details.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Meanwhile, others have worked towards developing analytical evidence of strong emergence.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Renormalization methods in theoretical physics enable physicists to study critical phenomena that are not tractable as the combination of their parts.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In 2009, Gu *et al.* presented a class of infinite physical systems that exhibits non-computable macroscopic properties.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] More precisely, if one could compute certain macroscopic properties of these systems from the microscopic description of these systems, then one would be able to solve computational problems known to be undecidable in computer science.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] These results concern infinite systems, finite systems being considered computable.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] However, macroscopic concepts which only apply in the limit of infinite systems, such as phase transitions and the renormalization group, are important for understanding and modeling real, finite physical systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Human beings are the basic elements of social systems, which perpetually interact and create, maintain, or untangle mutual social bonds.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Social bonds in social systems are perpetually changing in the sense of the ongoing reconfiguration of their structure.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] An early argument (1904–05) for the emergence of social formations can be found in Max Weber's most famous work, *The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism*.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Recently, the emergence of a new social system is linked with the emergence of order from nonlinear relationships among multiple interacting units, where multiple interacting units are individual thoughts, consciousness, and actions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In the case of the global economic system, under capitalism, growth, accumulation and innovation can be considered emergent processes where not only does technological processes sustain growth, but growth becomes the source of further innovations in a recursive, self-expanding spiral.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In this sense, the exponential trend of the growth curve reveals the presence of a long-term positive feedback among growth, accumulation, and innovation; and the emergence of new structures and institutions connected to the multi-scale process of growth.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] This is reflected in the work of Karl Polanyi, who traces the process by which labor and nature are converted into commodities in the passage from an economic system based on agriculture to one based on industry.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] This shift, along with the idea of the self-regulating market, set the stage not only for another economy but also for another society.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The principle of emergence is also brought forth when thinking about alternatives to the current economic system based on growth facing social and ecological limits.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Both degrowth and social ecological economics have argued in favor of a co-evolutionary perspective for theorizing about transformations that overcome the dependence of human wellbeing on economic growth.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Economic trends and patterns which emerge are studied intensively by economists.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Within the field of group facilitation and organization development, there have been a number of new group processes that are designed to maximize emergence and self-organization, by offering a minimal set of effective initial conditions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Examples of these processes include SEED-SCALE, appreciative inquiry, Future Search, the world cafe or knowledge cafe, Open Space Technology, and others (Holman, 2010).
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] These principles can be implemented utilizing a sequence of standardized tasks that self-assemble in individually specific ways utilizing recursive evaluative criteria.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Looking at emergence in the context of social and systems change, invites us to reframe our thinking on parts and wholes and their interrelation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Unlike machines, living systems at all levels of recursion - be it a sentient body, a tree, a family, an organisation, the education system, the economy, the health system, the political system etc - are continuously creating themselves.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] They are continually growing and changing along with their surrounding elements, and therefore are more than the sum of their parts.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Understanding emergence and what creates the conditions for different forms of emergence to occur, either insidious or nourishing vitality, is essential in the search for deep transformations.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The works of Nora Bateson and her colleagues at the International Bateson Institute delve into this.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Since 2012, they have been researching questions such as *what makes a living system ready to change?
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Can unforeseen ready-ness for change be nourished?* Here being ready is not thought of as being prepared, but rather as nourishing the flexibility we do not yet know will be needed.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] These inquiries challenge the common view that a theory of change is produced from an identified preferred goal or outcome.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Warm Data Labs are the fruit of their praxis, they are spaces for transcontextual mutual learning in which aphanipoetic phenomena unfold.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Having hosted hundreds of Warm Data processes with thousands of participants, they have found that these spaces of shared poly-learning across contexts lead to a realm of potential change, a necessarily obscured zone of wild interaction of unseen, unsaid, unknown flexibility.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] It is such flexibility that nourishes the ready-ing living systems require to respond to complex situations in new ways and change.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In other words, this readying process preludes what will emerge.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] When exploring questions of social change, it is important to ask ourselves, what is submerging in the current social imaginary and perhaps, rather than focus all our resources and energy on driving direct order responses, to nourish flexibility with ourselves, and the systems we are a part of.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Another approach that engages with the concept of emergence for social change is Theory U, where "deep emergence" is the result of self-transcending knowledge after a successful journey along the U through layers of awareness.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] This practice nourishes transformation at the inner-being level, which enables new ways of being, seeing and relating to emerge.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The concept of emergence has also been employed in the field of facilitation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In *Emergent Strategy*, adrienne maree brown defines emergent strategies as "ways for humans to practice complexity and grow the future through relatively simple interactions".
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In linguistics, the concept of emergence has been applied in the domain of stylometry to explain the interrelation between the syntactical structures of the text and the author style (Slautina, Marusenko, 2014).
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] It has also been argued that the structure and regularity of language grammar, or at least language change, is an emergent phenomenon.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] While each speaker merely tries to reach their own communicative goals, they use language in a particular way.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] If enough speakers behave in that way, language is changed.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In a wider sense, the norms of a language, i.e. the linguistic conventions of its speech society, can be seen as a system emerging from long-time participation in communicative problem-solving in various social circumstances.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The bulk conductive response of binary (RC) electrical networks with random arrangements, known as the universal dielectric response (UDR), can be seen as emergent properties of such physical systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Such arrangements can be used as simple physical prototypes for deriving mathematical formulae for the emergent responses of complex systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Internet traffic can also exhibit some seemingly emergent properties.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In the congestion control mechanism, TCP flows can become globally synchronized at bottlenecks, simultaneously increasing and then decreasing throughput in coordination.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Congestion, widely regarded as a nuisance, is possibly an emergent property of the spreading of bottlenecks across a network in high traffic flows which can be considered as a phase transition.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Some artificially intelligent (AI) computer applications simulate emergent behavior.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] One example is Boids, which mimics the swarming behavior of birds.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In religion, emergence grounds expressions of religious naturalism and syntheism in which a sense of the sacred is perceived in the workings of entirely naturalistic processes by which more complex forms arise or evolve from simpler forms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Pearce has used emergence to describe the experience of works of art in relation to contemporary neuroscience.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Practicing artist Leonel Moura, in turn, attributes to his "artbots" a real, if nonetheless rudimentary, creativity based on emergent principles.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Objects consist of components with properties differing from the object itself.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] We call these properties emergent because they did not exist at the component level.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The same applies to *artifacts* (structures, devices, tools, and even works of art).
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] They are created for a specific purpose and are therefore *subjectively* emergent: someone who doesn't understand the purpose can't use it.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] The artifact is the result of an *invention*: through a clever combination of components, something new is created with emergent properties and functionalities.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] This invention is often difficult to predict and therefore usually based on a chance *discovery*.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] An invention based on discovery is often improved through a feedback loop, making it more applicable.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] This is an example of *downward causation*.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Something similar occurs in nature: random mutations in genes rarely create a creature with new, emergent properties, increasing its chances of survival in a changing ecosystem.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Here too, through downward causation, new creatures can sometimes manipulate their ecosystem in such a way that their chances of survival are further increased.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] In both artifacts and living beings, certain components can be crucial to the emergent end result: the end result *supervenes* on these components.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Examples include: a construction error, a bug in a software program, an error in the genetic code, or the absence of a particular gene.
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] Both aspects: *supervenience* and the *unpredictability* of the emergent result are characteristic of *strong emergence* (see above).
[src:agent-based-modeling/emergence] (This definition, however, differs significantly from the definition in philosophical literature).
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo, the programming language, is a Lisp-style programming language with support for lists, “agentsets”, strings, input/output, and plotting.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Like the software itself, the programming language is also extensible using the built-in extension manager.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Many extensions are available, including support for arrays, tables, matrices as well as integrations with popular programming languages like R and Python.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo was designed by Uri Wilensky, in the spirit of the programming language Logo, to be "low threshold and no ceiling".
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] It teaches programming concepts using agents in the form of *turtles*, *patches*, *links* and the *observer*.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo was designed with multiple audiences in mind, in particular: teaching children in the education community, and for domain experts without a programming background to model related phenomena.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Thousands of scientific articles have been published using NetLogo.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The NetLogo environment enables exploration of emergent phenomena.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] It comes with an extensive models library including models in a variety of domains, such as economics, biology, physics, chemistry, psychology, and system dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo allows exploration by modifying switches, sliders, choosers, inputs, and other interface elements.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Beyond exploring, NetLogo allows authoring new models and modifying extant models.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo is open source and freely available from the NetLogo website.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] It is in use in a wide variety of educational contexts from elementary school to graduate school.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Many teachers make use of NetLogo in their curricula.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo is also widely used in scientific research having been used in several thousand research papers.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo was designed and authored by Uri Wilensky, director of Northwestern University's Center for Connected Learning and Computer-Based Modeling (CCL).
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Several books have been published about NetLogo.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo is free and open-source software, released under a GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] It is written in Scala and Java and runs on the Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] At its core is a hybrid interpreter/compiler that partially compiles user code to JVM bytecode.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo Web is a version that runs on JavaScript, instead of the JVM, so models may be run in a web browser.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] However, it does not yet have all features of the desktop version.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] NetLogo provides a built-in models library of over 600 models across multiple disciplines, including social science, psychology, mathematics, physics, biology, economics, game theory, and more.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Many of those models are part of the *An introduction to agent-based modeling: Modeling natural, social and engineered complex systems with NetLogo* textbook.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The **Wolf-Sheep Predation** model is simple multiagent model in NetLogo, which is shown in the screenshot above.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] It models the population growth of a predator/prey system over time.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The **Traffic Grid** model in NetLogo simulates vehicular movement and traffic light control on a two‑dimensional city grid.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Cars accelerate, decelerate, or stop depending on traffic lights, other vehicles, and a user‑defined speed limit.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The model is designed to demonstrate urban traffic dynamics and gridlock formation while allowing users to experiment with traffic management strategies.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The model allows users to test scenarios such as removing lights entirely (causing frequent gridlock), optimizing light phases for maximum flow, and adjusting car density to explore congestion thresholds.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The **Modeling Commons** is a web-based platform for sharing and collaborating on NetLogo models, hosted at modelingcommons.org.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Serving as the official NetLogo modeling forum, it allows users to upload, version, and manage NetLogo models, as well as discuss them and attach related files such as data or documentation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Users can search for models by name, author, tags, or content in the Info and Code tabs, and can create "child" variants of existing models to explore modifications while preserving lineage through a parent–child structure.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The platform also supports group-based permissions to manage collaboration and access, and automatically grants coauthor status to anyone who uploads a new version of a model.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] The site is designed to work with all modern web browsers and is most extensively tested on Chrome, Firefox, and Safari.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] HubNet is a technology that uses NetLogo to run participatory simulations in the classroom.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] In a participatory simulation, a whole group of users takes part in enacting the behavior of a system.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] Using an individual device, such as a networked computer or Texas Instruments graphing calculator, each user acts as a separate, independent agent.
[src:agent-based-modeling/netlogo] One example of a HubNet activity is *Tragedy of the Commons*, which models the economic problem called the tragedy of the commons.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] The original model is set in an $N\times N$ grid.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Agents are split into two groups and occupy the spaces of the grid and only one agent can occupy a space at a time.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Agents desire a fraction $B_{\textrm {a}}$ of their neighborhood (in this case, defined to be the eight adjacent agents around them) to be from the same group.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Increasing $B_{\textrm {a}}$ corresponds to increasing the agent's intolerance of outsiders.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Each round consists of agents checking their neighborhood to see if the fraction of neighbors B that matches their group—ignoring empty spaces—is greater than or equal to $B_{\textrm {a}}$ .
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] If $B<B_{\textrm {a}}$ , then the agent will choose to relocate to a vacant spot where $B\geq B_{\textrm {a}}$ .
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] This continues until every agent is satisfied.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Every agent is not guaranteed to be satisfied, and in these cases, it is of interest to study the patterns (if any) of the agent dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] While studying population dynamics of two groups of equal size, Schelling found a threshold $B_{\textrm {seg}}$ such that $B_{\textrm {a}}<B_{\textrm {seg}}$ leads to a random population configuration and $B_{\textrm {a}}\geq B_{\textrm {seg}}$ leads to a segregated configuration.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] This points to how individuals with even a small amount of in-group preference can form segregated societies.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] There are different parameterizations and variants of the model and a 'unified' approach is presented in allowing the simulations to explore the thresholds for different segregation events to occur.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] There have been observations that the fundamental dynamics of the agents resemble the mechanics used in the Ising model of ferromagnetism.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] This primarily relies on the similar nature in which each occupied grid location calculates an aggregate measure based upon the similarities of the adjacent grid cells.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] If each agent produces a satisfaction based upon their homophilic satisfaction threshold as ${\textstyle [0,1]}$ then the summation of those values can provide an indication for the segregation of the state that is analogous to the clustering of the aligned spins in a magnetic material.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Each agent produces a binary value, so that for each grid configuration of agents of both groups, a vector can be produced of the remain due to satisfaction or not.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] The overall satisfaction from the remain states of all the agents can be computed; ${\textstyle R=\sum _{n=1}^{N}r(m_{n})}$ .
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] R then provides a measure for the amount of homogeneity (segregation) on the grid and can be used with the maximum possible value (total sum of agents) as a 'density' of segregation over the simulation of movements as is performed in.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] The canonical Schelling model does not consider variables which may affect the agent's ability to relocate positions in the grid.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] The work of Hatna and Benenson investigates a model extension where the utility available to agents to move governs this action.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] It can explain some of the patterns seen where groups do not segregate due to the financial barrier homogeneous zones produce as a result of high demand.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] The consideration of the financial aspect is also investigated in two other papers, in 2012 and 2009.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] The work of Mantzaris further develops this concept of the importance of the monetary factor in the decision making, and uses it to extend the model with a dual dynamic where agents radiate their income store whenever a movement is made.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] This also provides a means to produce a more complete model where the trace of the entropy is non-decreasing and adds support that social systems obey the Second law of thermodynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/schelling-s-model-of-segregation] Schelling's model has also been studied from a game-theoretic perspective: In *Schelling games*, agents strategically strive to maximize their utilities by relocating to a position with the highest fraction of neighboring agents from the same group.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence systems consist typically of a population of simple agents or boids interacting locally with one another and with their environment.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The inspiration often comes from nature, especially biological systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The agents follow very simple rules, and although there is no centralized control structure dictating how individual agents should behave, local, and to a certain degree random, interactions between such agents lead to the emergence of "intelligent" global behavior, unknown to the individual agents.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Examples of swarm intelligence in natural systems include ant colonies, bee colonies, bird flocking, hawks hunting, animal herding, bacterial growth, fish schooling and microbial intelligence.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The application of swarm principles to robots is called *swarm robotics* while *swarm intelligence* refers to the more general set of algorithms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] *Swarm prediction* has been used in the context of forecasting problems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Similar approaches to those proposed for swarm robotics are considered for genetically modified organisms in synthetic collective intelligence.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Boids is an artificial life program, developed by Craig Reynolds in 1986, which simulates flocking.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It was published in 1987 in the proceedings of the ACM SIGGRAPH conference.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The name "boid" corresponds to a shortened version of "bird-oid object", which refers to a bird-like object.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] As with most artificial life simulations, Boids is an example of emergent behavior; that is, the complexity of Boids arises from the interaction of individual agents (the boids, in this case) adhering to a set of simple rules.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] More complex rules can be added, such as obstacle avoidance and goal seeking.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Self-propelled particles (SPP), also referred to as the *Vicsek model*, was introduced in 1995 by Vicsek *et al.* as a special case of the boids model introduced in 1986 by Reynolds.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] A swarm is modelled in SPP by a collection of particles that move with a constant speed but respond to a random perturbation by adopting at each time increment the average direction of motion of the other particles in their local neighbourhood.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] SPP models predict that swarming animals share certain properties at the group level, regardless of the type of animals in the swarm.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarming systems give rise to emergent behaviours which occur at many different scales, some of which are turning out to be both universal and robust.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It has become a challenge in theoretical physics to find minimal statistical models that capture these behaviours.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Social Potential Fields, developed in 1999 by John H.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Reif and Hongyan Wang , is one of the earliest models for Swarm Intelligence, developed for use for autonomous control of robot swarm systems that may consist of from hundreds to perhaps tens of thousands or more autonomous robots.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It is the first paper to apply a potential field model to distributed autonomous multi-robot control.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] A Social Potential Field defines simple artificial force laws between pairs of robots or robot groups.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] These force laws are inverse-power force laws, incorporating both attraction and repulsion, similar but more general compared to the force laws found in molecular dynamics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] As one of simplest examples, they define a force law where attraction dominates over long distances and repulsion dominates on short distances.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The force laws can be distinct between various robots.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] An individual robot's motion is controlled by the resultant artificial force imposed by other robots and other components of the system.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields approach is distributed since the force calculations and motion control can be done in an asynchronous and distributed manner.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Using specially tailored force laws, they demonstrate complex behaviors and what might be viewed as "social relations' among robots.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Therefore, the model was termed "Social Potential Fields”.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] They demonstrated by computer simulations that the method can yield interesting and useful behaviors among robots, including clustering, guarding, escorting, patrolling, etc.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The 1999 paper envisioned many industrial and military applications such as assembling, transporting, hazardous inspection. patrolling, and military control of swarm systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Their simulations showed the social potential fields method is robust in that the method can tolerate errors in sensors and actuators.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields paper also extended the social potential fields model to use spring laws as force laws.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Evolutionary algorithms (EA), particle swarm optimization (PSO), differential evolution (DE), ant colony optimization (ACO) and their variants dominate the field of nature-inspired metaheuristics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] This list includes algorithms published up to circa the year 2000.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] A large number of more recent metaphor-inspired metaheuristics have started to attract criticism in the research community for hiding their lack of novelty behind an elaborate metaphor.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] For algorithms published since that time, see List of metaphor-based metaheuristics.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Popular modern post-2000 examples include Grey Wolf Optimization (GWO), which replicates the dynamic hunting mechanisms and social leadership hierarchies of wolves in nature.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Metaheuristics lack a confidence in a solution.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] When appropriate parameters are determined, and when sufficient convergence stage is achieved, they often find a solution that is optimal, or near close to optimum – nevertheless, if one does not know optimal solution in advance, a quality of a solution is not known.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In spite of this obvious drawback it has been shown that these types of algorithms work well in practice, and have been extensively researched, and developed.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] One such instance is Ant-inspired Monte Carlo algorithm for Minimum Feedback Arc Set where this has been achieved probabilistically via hybridization of Monte Carlo algorithm with Ant Colony Optimization technique.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Ant colony optimization (ACO), introduced by Dorigo in his doctoral dissertation, is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] ACO is a probabilistic technique useful in problems that deal with finding better paths through graphs.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Artificial 'ants'—simulation agents—locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Natural ants lay down pheromones directing each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The simulated 'ants' similarly record their positions and the quality of their solutions, so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate for better solutions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Particle swarm optimization (PSO) is a global optimization algorithm for dealing with problems in which a best solution can be represented as a point or surface in an n-dimensional space.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Hypotheses are plotted in this space and seeded with an initial velocity, as well as a communication channel between the particles.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Particles then move through the solution space, and are evaluated according to some fitness criterion after each timestep.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Over time, particles are accelerated towards those particles within their communication grouping which have better fitness values.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The main advantage of such an approach over other global minimization strategies such as simulated annealing is that the large number of members that make up the particle swarm make the technique impressively resilient to the problem of local minima.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) is method of amplifying the collective intelligence of networked human groups using control algorithms modeled after natural swarms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] ASI has also been used to enable groups of doctors to generate diagnoses with significantly higher accuracy than traditional methods.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] ASI has been used by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United Nations to help forecast famines in hotspots around the world.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarm Intelligence-based techniques can be used in a number of applications.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The U.S. military is investigating swarm techniques for controlling unmanned vehicles.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The European Space Agency is thinking about an orbital swarm for self-assembly and interferometry.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] NASA is investigating the use of swarm technology for planetary mapping.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Bekey discusses the possibility of using swarm intelligence to control nanobots within the body for the purpose of killing cancer tumors.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Conversely al-Rifaie and Aber have used stochastic diffusion search to help locate tumours.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence (SI) is increasingly applied in Internet of Things (IoT) systems, and by association to Intent-Based Networking (IBN), due to its ability to handle complex, distributed tasks through decentralized, self-organizing algorithms.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence has also been applied for data mining and cluster analysis.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Ant-based models are further subject of modern management theory.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence can be used in many practical areas where multiple simple agents work together to solve complex problems efficiently.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It is commonly applied in optimization problems, such as route planning, scheduling, and resource allocation, where algorithms inspired by ants and birds help find the best solutions.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In robotics, swarm intelligence is used for coordinating multiple robots in tasks like search and rescue, warehouse automation, and environmental monitoring.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It is also widely used in network systems for efficient routing of data in the internet and wireless sensor networks.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In addition, swarm intelligence plays an important role in traffic and transportation systems, where it helps in traffic signal control, vehicle routing, and reducing congestion in smart cities.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In machine learning and data mining, it is used for feature selection, clustering, and improving model performance.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It is also applied in power systems for load balancing and energy optimization, especially in smart grids.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Furthermore, swarm intelligence is used in healthcare and bioinformatics for tasks like drug discovery and gene analysis, and in gaming and simulations to create realistic group behaviors such as crowd movement or flocking.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The use of swarm intelligence in telecommunication networks has also been researched, in the form of ant-based routing.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] This was pioneered separately by Dorigo et al. and Hewlett-Packard in the mid-1990s, with a number of variants existing.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Basically, this uses a probabilistic routing table rewarding/reinforcing the route successfully traversed by each "ant" (a small control packet) which flood the network.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] As the system behaves stochastically and is therefore lacking repeatability, there are large hurdles to commercial deployment.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Mobile media and new technologies have the potential to change the threshold for collective action due to swarm intelligence (Rheingold: 2002, P175).
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The location of transmission infrastructure for wireless communication networks is an important engineering problem involving competing objectives.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] A minimal selection of locations (or sites) are required subject to providing adequate area coverage for users.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] A very different, ant-inspired swarm intelligence algorithm, stochastic diffusion search (SDS), has been successfully used to provide a general model for this problem, related to circle packing and set covering.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] It has been shown that the SDS can be applied to identify suitable solutions even for large problem instances.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have also used ant-based routing in assigning aircraft arrivals to airport gates.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] At Southwest Airlines a software program uses swarm theory, or swarm intelligence—the idea that a colony of ants works better than one alone.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Each pilot acts like an ant searching for the best airport gate.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] "The pilot learns from his experience what's the best for him, and it turns out that that's the best solution for the airline," Douglas A.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] As a result, the "colony" of pilots always go to gates they can arrive at and depart from quickly.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The program can even alert a pilot of plane back-ups before they happen.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] "We can anticipate that it's going to happen, so we'll have a gate available," Lawson says.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Artists are using swarm technology as a means of creating complex interactive systems or simulating crowds.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Tim Burton's *Batman Returns* also made use of swarm technology for showing the movements of a group of bats.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have used swarm theory to simulate passengers boarding a plane.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Southwest Airlines researcher Douglas A.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Lawson used an ant-based computer simulation employing only six interaction rules to evaluate boarding times using various boarding methods.(Miller, 2010, xii-xviii).
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Networks of distributed users can be organized into "human swarms" through the implementation of real-time closed-loop control systems.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Developed by Louis Rosenberg in 2015, human swarming, also called artificial swarm intelligence, allows the collective intelligence of interconnected groups of people online to be harnessed.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The collective intelligence of the group often exceeds the abilities of any one member of the group.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In one such study, swarms of human radiologists connected together were tasked with diagnosing chest x-rays and demonstrated a 33% reduction in diagnostic errors as compared to the traditional human methods, and a 22% improvement over traditional machine-learning.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The University of California San Francisco (UCSF) School of Medicine released a preprint in 2021 about the diagnosis of MRI images by small groups of collaborating doctors.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The study showed a 23% increase in diagnostic accuracy when using Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) technology compared to majority voting.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Swarm grammars are swarms of stochastic grammars that can be evolved to describe complex properties such as found in art and architecture.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] These grammars interact as agents behaving according to rules of swarm intelligence.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Such behavior can also suggest deep learning algorithms, in particular when mapping of such swarms to neural circuits is considered.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The "creativity" of this hybrid swarm system has been analysed under the philosophical light of the "rhizome" in the context of Deleuze's "Orchid and Wasp" metaphor.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] A more recent work of al-Rifaie et al., "Swarmic Sketches and Attention Mechanism", introduces a novel approach deploying the mechanism of 'attention' by adapting SDS to selectively attend to detailed areas of a digital canvas.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Once the attention of the swarm is drawn to a certain line within the canvas, the capability of PSO is used to produce a 'swarmic sketch' of the attended line.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The swarms move throughout the digital canvas in an attempt to satisfy their dynamic roles—attention to areas with more details—associated with them via their fitness function.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Having associated the rendering process with the concepts of attention, the performance of the participating swarms creates a unique, non-identical sketch each time the 'artist' swarms embark on interpreting the input line drawings.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In other works, while PSO is responsible for the sketching process, SDS controls the attention of the swarm.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] In a similar work, "Swarmic Paintings and Colour Attention", non-photorealistic images are produced using SDS algorithm which, in the context of this work, is responsible for colour attention.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] The "computational creativity" of the above-mentioned systems are discussed in through the two prerequisites of creativity (i.e. freedom and constraints) within the swarm intelligence's two infamous phases of exploration and exploitation.
[src:agent-based-modeling/swarm-intelligence] Michael Theodore and Nikolaus Correll use swarm intelligent art installation to explore what it takes to have engineered systems to appear lifelike.
